You can set the values for an insert statement in Actian 4GL using either of these methods:
1. By specifying a literal value for each field, like this:
```4gl
insert into customers (name, address)
values ('Acme Corporation', '123 Main Street');
```
2. Or by referencing a variable that holds your data, such as this one:
```4gl
let c = new customer();
c.name = 'Acme Corporation';
c.address = '123 Main Street';
insert into customers (name, address)
values (c);
```
Example:
Both methods work similarly here, so we can use either one of them for our example:
```4gl
insert into orders (customer_id, order_number)
values(123456, 'Order #27');
```

You can define a new class using the following syntax:
```4gl
class MyClass {
    attributes;
    methods;
}
MyClass = new();
```

You can remove any number of attributes from your object using either of these methods:
1. By specifying a literal value for the attribute, such as this:
```4gl
insert into customers (customer_id, name)
values ('AC678', 'Acme Corporation');
```
2. Or by referencing a variable that holds your data, like this one:
```4gl
let c = new customer();
c.address = '123 Main Street';
delete c.phone;
insert into customers (customer_id, name, address)
values (c);
```
Example:
The same rules apply here too, so we can use either method for our example:
```4gl
insert into orders (order_number, customer_id, ship_to_address)
values ('Order #13', 123456, '123 Main Street');
delete orders.items[2].price;
```

The default clause specifies the initial value for an attribute:
```4gl
class person {
    name;
    age integer not null default 30;
}
```

The syntax for defining a procedure in Actian 4GL is:
```4gl
procedure name {
    /* procedural code here */
}
```

You can use the = clause in your insert statement to set the initial value of a new object attribute. For example:
i = new vehicle();
i.brand = 'Volvo';
i.model = '850 GLT';
insert into cars (brand, model) values (i.brand, i.model);
In this example, we first declare a new vehicle object (i). Then, we set its brand and model attributes to the desired values using the = clause in our insert statement.

You can use the delete clause in your update or delete statement to remove an attribute from an object. For example:
i = vehicle('Volvo', '850 GLT');
delete i.model;
In this example, we first retrieve the desired vehicle object (i) using its brand and model attributes as parameters for the function. Then, we use the delete clause in our statement to remove the model attribute from that object.

You can create a procedural variable with an initial value of zero like this:
```4gl
procedure name;
```
where 'name' is the name of your procedure. The opening parenthesis (') and closing parenthesis (') define the scope for your procedure, which includes all its local variables and parameters. Inside this scope, you can declare other variables such as attributes or enumerated types. For example:
```4gl
procedure greet(title varchar, message varchar) {
  title = 'Mr.';
  message = 'Hello, how are you today? I am glad to see you again.';
}
```
In this example, we have declared two attributes – title and message. Both of them are of the same data type (varchar in this case). We also set their initial values by using the DEFAULT clause within our procedural statement. After declaring the variables, we use them in our code such as setting the title attribute to 'Mr.' or sending a greeting message to the user.

You can display the output of an insert statement in your Actian 4GL code using either of these methods:
1. By specifying a literal value for each field, like this:
```4gl
insert into customers (name, address)
values ('Acme Corporation', '123 Main Street');
```
2. Or by referencing a variable that holds your data, such as this one:
```4gl
let c = new customer();
c.name = 'Acme Corporation';
c.address = '123 Main Street';
insert into customers (name, address)
values (c);
```
Example:
Both methods work similarly here, so we can use either one of them for our example:
```4gl
output ‘Added the following customer:’;
output c.name;
output ‘ to the database.’;
```

You can access your object’s attributes using their names or by referencing them with a variable reference. For example, if we have an Order class and want to get its name, we could do either:
```4gl
order = new order('ACME CORP');
console.log(order.name);
```
Or just use the variable reference itself:
```4gl
let c = new customer();
c.address = '123 Main Street';
console.log(c.shipToAddress);
```
Example:
The same rules apply here too, so we can use either method for our example:
```4gl
let project = new project('ACME CORP', :enddate);
project.name = 'My Project';
console.log(project.name);
```

You can use the 'update statement' to modify several columns of an existing table:
```4gl
update tablename set column1 = 'new value',
column2 = 'other new value';
where (condition);
commit;
```
Example:
```4gl
update projects set name = 'Games project',
duedate = 2023-05-15;
where (name > :oldname and duedate < 2023-06-01);
commit;
```

The delete statement removes data from your database:
```4gl
delete from tablename;
where (condition);
commit;
```
Example:
```4gl
delete from projects;
where (name > :oldname and duedate < 2023-06-01);
commit;
```
